Chapter One
Koren
4:30 AM, Itania Time. Koren hated getting up so early. Mainly because he was responsible for waking up the rest of the platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, put on his assault vest, packed up his things from the locker, and carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a breathing apparatus, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots crunching on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had to think of every possible way to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm, because half the time it didn't go off, and all that could be heard from the speaker was a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Koren turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemici approaching.
"Yes," Koren replied.
"What method are you going to use this time?"
Koren hadn't even had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Cress, and a few others hurried out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Cress said.
"What woke you up?" Koren asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use today to wake everyone up. Second, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," a soldier named Ravek replied. "You know how awful that breakfast is."
Koren said, "You're right, Ravek Corporal." He reached out and pressed the switch. A shrill alarm immediately rang out in the barracks. He heard people shouting inside, accompanied by the sound of hurried footsteps.
"My goodness, Valturi," Nemici said. "I thought they would have already learned to get up with you by now."
"My brothers in basic training did," Koren said, pointing at Harris, Cress, and Ravek. "But to be fair, their squad leaders and platoon commanders all knew to get up before their soldiers did."
Several seconds later, the rest of the squad ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked drowsy, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Koren said cheerfully.
"With all due respect, sir, why did you wake us up that way?" a squad member (sergeant) asked.
"Because those regular alarms are just junk. And Daybreak never sleeps in," Koren said.
"Take your personal belongings," Koren continued. As a lieutenant and the deputy commander of the company, he was responsible for assisting Captain Bolding Shaw, the company commander, in overseeing and leading the company. "We won't be coming back. Sergeants and lieutenants, you have 15 minutes to do your final checks and bring along today's rations for yourselves and your soldiers."
The members of the Exodus platoon quickly dispersed. They were part of the 2nd Shock Division of the 2nd Army Group. Before the merger, they had originally been two separate platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite platoon, and Koren felt a complex mix of emotions about being promoted to lieutenant, for there were many reasons behind it.
Koren and Lieutenant Nemici walked side by side along the well-lit base road, where the lights on both sides were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. In order to strike them, Daybreak had begun employing "Wild Weasel" tactics in both the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hellpioneers," Nemici said dryly. "Where exactly are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside Ianlos City. We're being sent to support the ground offensive," Koren said, taking a puff of his cigarette. He somewhat resented Cress for getting him hooked on cigarettes, but thinking about the past year of countless battles they had endured, he let it go, so he said nothing.
"That's really bad. The frontline situation is tight," Nemici murmured. "All the news coming out of here is 'support the war, aid the Kurgan frontline,' why not support the Holan frontline instead?"
"Well said, brother," Koren said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll be going with the first armored squad. No walking needed. Captain Shaw should be there."
"Captain Shaw let us ride?" Nemici asked, somewhat surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he isn't as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not annoying either."
Koren raised his thumb and index finger, pressing the microphone at his throat, while shifting his backpack to his back. "Exodus platoon, all units, assemble at the West Yard after completing your tasks. We will depart at 05:00 with the first armored squad."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Ravek were all lower-ranking non-commissioned officers. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had always been close friends. Koren felt as though he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since a week ago, when the former platoon leader was hit by a Daybreak sniper and retired due to injury, Cress had begun leading the second squad.
As they approached the vehicle yard, Koren and Nemici's eyes fell on approximately eight Kronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were in good working order. Koren quickly spotted Captain Bolding Shaw in the crowd, who was talking with the armored squad commander. As they approached, Captain Shaw looked at them and came forward to meet them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemici... Lieutenant Valturi..." he said. Koren slowed his steps. Captain Shaw looked at Koren's pistol holster and then looked up. "Should the platoon be ready by now?"
